	<tr><td bgcolor="#ffffff">
		Hey Bikash,
<br>
<br>My comment went in before i read your own comment. IMHO, a) b) and
c) describe the DNS system. So i don't see any reason to change it.
<br>
<br>More specifically, about (b). The replication scheme is obviously
implemented in most DNS servers. A DNS master server is Authoritative
for a zone and replicates it to any server which has been declared as a
slave DNS server for it. The whois records list all the DNS servers for
a particular domain (NS) records. You also have DNS caches that are
implemented at each ISP level and cache the information they receive
from the master DNS. Your architecture has to take this caching system
in account (if we wouldn't cache the information, the DNS traffic even
on xwiki.com will be higher that the HTTP, and the time to resolve any
server's name before making a single request would be huge).
<br>
<br>
a whois on xwiki.com answers you :
<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Name Server: LANAI.XPERTNET.BIZ
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Name Server: MAUI.XPERTNET.BIZ
<br>
<br>
Then if we look at the DNS configuration for xwiki.com :
<br>
<br>
mac:~ erwan$ host -t NS xwiki.com   
<br>
xwiki.com name server maui.xpertnet.biz.
<br>
xwiki.com name server lanai.xpertnet.biz.
<br>
<br>
and then, on lanai.xpertnet.biz (our DNS master) :
<br>
<br>
zone "xwiki.com" {
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;type master;
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;file "/etc/bind/xwiki.com.hosts";
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;};
<br>
<br>
and finally, on maui (our DNS slave) :
<br>
<br>
zone "xwiki.com" {
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;type slave;
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;masters {
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;192.168.0.8;
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;};
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;file "/var/cache/bind/xwiki.com.hosts";
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;};
<br>
<br>
(192.168.0.8 is lanai's internal IP address).
<br>
<br>
I really think a DNS server with a MySQL backend updated by your application will do the job.
<br>
<br>
Erwan
