	<tr><td bgcolor="#ffffff">
		I don't think making name resolution P2P in our own zone is a good idea.
<br>
<br>
- any peer elected as DNS server will be able to hijack the DNS of p2p.xwiki.com (or p2pwiki.com) for his own purpose
<br>
<br>
- i don't see any benefit over the standard master/slave architecture
where a master server that we manage is replicated to slaves and caches
all across the Internet.
<br>
<br>- there might be a TTL (Time To Live) problem when creating a new
entry (server) in the zone, but it can be alleviated by reducing the
said TTL. I mean that changes take a certain time to be replicated on
the slaves. The TTL parameter allow to reduce this time, but increase
the load on the servers.
<br>
<br>
Proposal:
<br>
<br>
- install mydns or pdns on a test server. If you need one i guess we can provide you with a test environment.
<br>
- implement a webapp/webservice that updates the server's backend 
<br>
- check that you can insert/remove/update records
<br>
- verify that name resolution works with your server using standard NS debugging tools (host, dig, zonecheck ...)
<br>
<br>

