	<tr><td bgcolor="#ffffff">
It's a tough choice, wether to use the peers for the resolution or not.
As Erwan has stated, the DNS system is redundant and fail-safe as
itself, so the reason for using peers for the name resolution should
not be a question of availability. However the load of all the p2p
clients connected to the central registry to gather the information
back to the central database could be crazy.
<br>
<br>
However when we first discussed resolution, we had been talking about using redirections.. 
<br>
<br>ludovic.p2p.xwiki.com could send the IP of the closest node and
then you would be either servered directly by the node (which relays)
or redirected to ludovic.peer.p2p.xwiki.com (a peer serving the wiki)
or ludovic.local.p2p.xwiki.com (yourself because you have a copy) or
ludovic.orig.p2p.xwiki.com (the master wiki).
<br>
<br>This could be a way to involve the peers in the name resolution..
Only the nodes would be connected to the central registry. Individual
users would be connected to a set of nodes. The nodes would send back
the info about the users to the central wiki.
<br>
<br>Something like that needs to be designed otherwise it's not going
to work. In terms of load it's important to state that the P2P installs
need to have some permanent connection to the network one way or
another.
<br>
<br>
PS: we don't need to build everything right away, but the architecture needs to be scalable.
	</td></tr>
