	<tr><td bgcolor="#ffffff">
		I've made a proposal for the P2P Name resolution using a diagram with Inkscape (SVG) on the wiki: <a href="http://www.xwiki.org/xwiki/bin/download/Dev/Design+Issues/p2pxwiki-resolution.png">http://www.xwiki.org/xwiki/bin/download/Dev/Design+Issues/p2pxwiki-resolution.png</a>
<br>
<br>The idea is that the P2P XWiki's are connected permanently using
nodes. The permanent connections allow to send information up the
permanent connection to give the localisation of the P2P client to the
central registry.
<br>
<br>DNS resolution would then either send back the IP of the closest
node if the P2P client is behing a firewall or send back the IP of the
machine itself. If a other P2P client has a replica of a wiki his IP or
the closest node could also be valid IP's in the DNS registry.
<br>
<br>Now with this system the availability is dependent on the
availability of the central registry and the DNS cluster. This system
needs to be designed to be clustered and solid (2 datacenters). This
single point of failure is the price to pay to be compatible with
standard browsers and not only users having the P2P XWiki client.
<br>
<br>The P2P XWiki client could work only by querying the node which
finds other wikis using the node system. That could be an enhancement
for the users of the P2P XWiki (working without the central registry by
discovering close users). </td></tr>
