	<tr><td bgcolor="#ffffff">
		After looking at the programmer's guide <a href="http://www.jxta.org/docs/JxtaProgGuide_v2.3.pdf,">http://www.jxta.org/docs/JxtaProgGuide_v2.3.pdf,</a> <br>
here is a small summary of features in JXTA. 
<br>
<br>
- key design goal: modular
<br>
<br>
- The essential aspects of the architecture are: 
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;+ The use of XML documents (advertisements) to describe network resources.
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;+ Abstraction of pipes to peers, and peers to endpoints without reliance
<br>
upon a central naming/addressing authority such as DNS.
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;+ A uniform peer addressing scheme (peer IDs)
<br>
<br>
<br>
- JXTA allows peers to be combined together to form a group. It provides
<br>
basic services such as discovery service - to search for peer group
<br>
resources; membership service - to accept/reject new membership
<br>
applications to a group by group members collectively; access service -
<br>
validate requests made by one peer to another; pipe service - to create and
<br>
manage pipe connections among peers; resolver service - to send generic
<br>
query requests to other peers; and monitoring service - to allow monitoring
<br>
of other peers in the same group. 
<br>
<br>
- All peer belong to a default group to start with. The groups
<br>
form parent/child relationship and form a hierarchy. Moreover, one peer
<br>
can be part of multiple groups. 
<br>
<br>
- The services are broken down into peer services and peer group services. 
<br>
<br>
- Pipes: JXTA peers use pipes to send messages to one another. Pipes
<br>
are asynchronous, unidirectional and unreliable. pipe endpoints are
<br>
dynamically bound to peer endpoints at runtime. pipes can have endpoints
<br>
that are connected to different peers at different times, or may not be
<br>
connected at all. JXTA also provides secure unicast pipes, a secure and
<br>
reliable variant of unicast pipes. There is a reliable library and 
<br>
socket interface that is provided as two way communication channel on top
<br>
of unidirectional pipes. 
<br>
<br>
- Security: JXTA considers all aspects of security - confidentiality -
<br>
contents of messages are not disclosed; authentication: guarantees that
<br>
sender is who he/she claims to be; authorization: guarantees that sender
<br>
is authorized to send; data integrity: guarantees that message was not
<br>
modified accidentally or intentionally in transit; refutability: guarantees
<br>
that message is transmitted by properly identified sender and is not a
<br>
replay of an earlier message. 
<br>
<br>
Verdict: It appears to be a good place to bootstrap the implementation for developing p2pxwiki prototype.
