	<tr><td bgcolor="#ffffff">
		I saw an "interesting" project called p2psockets (<a href="http://p2psockets.jxta.org/docs/tutorials/2.html#footnote5">http://p2psockets.jxta.org/docs/tutorials/2.html#footnote5</a>)
built on top of JXTA. This project provides the standard socket APIs
using p2p network (hiding the complexity of peer discovery and binding
behind the scene). The interesting aspect is it has been used to
develop Peer-to-Peer Web Servers, Servlets, JSPs, and XML-RPC Clients
and Servers. <br>
<br>
The webpage above even gives Wiki as an example application that can be built using p2psockets. It gives JSPWiki (<a href="http://www.jspwiki.org/Wiki.jsp">http://www.jspwiki.org/Wiki.jsp</a>)
as an example- I am not sure if JSPWiki uses p2psockets (my first
impression is that JSPWiki is used as a generic example of a wiki, and
not necessarily something that uses p2psockets). <br>
<br>
I wanted to document some of my experience with p2psockets so far: 
<br>
It is claimed that servlets work right out of the box without any
modifications, by using the included modified webserver with p2psockets
(the webserver is a modification of Jetty). I tried this by using the
xwiki war but couldn't get it to work. <br>
<br>
Using p2psocket to build p2pxwiki is an interesting design option that
can be explored. It may ease the implementation effort, however many
issues such as replication, registry to allow uniqueness in wiki names,
browser based access without changing any configuration on client side
(p2psocket advocates using a proxy on the client that talks to a
p2psocket based proxy server) still remain. However, it may be worth
exploring. <br>
<br>

	</td></tr>
