	<tr><td bgcolor="#ffffff">
This is really interesting.. You should indeed reuse the Jetty port,
the XML-RPC client and the Smart Cache module (which allows HTTP
access).
<br>
<br>If you have a smart cache module (or a modification of it) on nodes
(machines not behind firewalls), they can relay standard browser over
the P2P network..
<br>
<br>Otherwise your P2P client would be a modified jetty to be jxta
aware with a xwiki behind it. Replication would occur transparently
through the modified xml-rpc client to go over the P2Psockets.. The
smart cache node would be added on top of it to accept HTTP requests
from standard browser.
<br>
<br>You still need to registry I think to tell the browser or anybody
who has a copy of the wiki.. This can function using XML-RPC calls over
the modified xml-rpc client to call the "registry" peer..
<br>
<br>So you need to implement XML-RPC method for the registry updates.
The registry plugin would still update the DNS (unless you find a way
using P2Psockets to handle the DNS issue).
<br>
<br>
Ludovic
